SIMPLE: reclaim
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Reclaim
<hw>Re*claim"</hw> <pr>(r⟦emac⟧*kl⟦amac⟧m")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<def>To claim back; to demand the return of as a right; to attempt to
recover possession of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A tract of land [Holland] snatched from an element perpetually
<qex>reclaiming</qex> its prior occupancy.</q> <rj><qau>W.
Coxe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reclaim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Reclaim
<hw>Re*claim"</hw> <pr>(r⟦esl⟧*kl⟦amac⟧m")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Reclaimed</conjf>
<pr>(r⟦esl⟧*kl⟦amac⟧md")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Reclaiming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧clamer</ets>, L. <ets>reclamare</ets>,
<ets>reclamatum</ets>, to cry out against; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- +
<ets>clamare</ets> to call or cry aloud. See <er>Claim</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To call back, as a hawk to the wrist in falconry, by a
certain customary call.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To call back from flight or disorderly action; to
call to, for the purpose of subduing or quieting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The headstrong horses hurried Octavius . . . along, and were deaf
to his <qex>reclaiming</qex> them.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To reduce from a wild to a tamed state; to bring
under discipline; -- said especially of birds trained for the chase, but
also of other animals.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧An eagle well
<xex>reclaimed</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Hence: To reduce to a desired state by discipline,
labor, cultivation, or the like; to rescue from being wild, desert,
waste, submerged, or the like; <as>as, to <ex>reclaim</ex> wild land,
overflowed land, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To call back to rectitude from moral wandering or
transgression; to draw back to correct deportment or course of life; to
reform.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is the intention of Providence, in all the various expressions
of his goodness, to <qex>reclaim</qex> mankind.</q>
<rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To correct; to reform; -- said of things.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your error, in time <qex>reclaimed</qex>, will be venial.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir E. Hoby.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To exclaim against; to gainsay.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To reform; recover; restore; amend;
correct.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reclaim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Reclaim
<hw>Re*claim"</hw> <pr>(r⟦esl⟧*kl⟦amac⟧m")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To cry out in opposition or contradiction; to exclaim
against anything; to contradict; to take exceptions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Scripture <qex>reclaims</qex>, and the whole Catholic church
<qex>reclaims</qex>, and Christian ears would not hear it.</q>
<rj><qau>Waterland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At a later period Grote <qex>reclaimed</qex> strongly against
Mill's setting Whately above Hamilton.</q> <rj><qau>Bain.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bring anyone back from evil courses; to
reform.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They, hardened more by what might most <qex>reclaim</qex>,⟦br⟧
Grieving to see his glory, . . . took envy.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To draw back; to give way.</def> <mark>[R. &
Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reclaim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Reclaim
<hw>Re*claim"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of reclaiming, or the
state of being reclaimed; reclamation; recovery.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reclaimable</ent>⟦br⟧
